            <div type="general">
               <p xml:space="preserve">Nefza (formerly Djebel Abiod / Ǧabal Abyaḏ̣) is a small town in the North West Tunisian governorate of Béja, located in a valley between the Kroumir and the Mogod mountains. The Sidi el Barrak (Sīdi l-Baṛṛāg) Dam which is situated next to Nefza supplies water for different parts of the country. Beside its breath-taking arboreous nature, the Nefza region is famous for the kaki fruit called <hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">krīma</hi>, which is the town’s symbol as well.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <p xml:space="preserve">This dialect was linguistically investigated within the TUNOCENT project, which resulted in the following publications: <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:R32S6HU7">Naddari (2024)</rs> 
                     and <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:ERM2XT6C">Naddari (2023)</rs></p>
